Technical Specification: DroidBridge P2P (Phase 1)
1. Project Overview
DroidBridge is a high-performance, low-latency synchronization service designed to bridge the gap between two Android devices. In Phase 1, the system must facilitate the real-time mirroring of System Notifications (SMS) and Telephony Events (Incoming Calls) from a Source Device (Xiaomi) to a Sink Device (Pixel) via a persistent WebSocket tunnel over LAN.

2. System Architecture & Role Definitions
A. Server Role (The Sink - Google Pixel 9 Pro XL)
Networking: Hosts a Ktor WebSocket Server (CIO Engine) on a dedicated port (default: 8080).

Service Layer: A Sticky Foreground Service that manages the Ktor engine and keeps the CPU partially awake via Partial WakeLock.

Notification Engine: Receives JSON payloads and utilizes NotificationManager to inject "Virtual Notifications" into the system.

Watch Synchronization: By injecting notifications with PRIORITY_MAX and VISIBILITY_PUBLIC, the OS automatically pushes these alerts to any connected Wear OS device.

B. Client Role (The Source - Xiaomi 11T Pro)
Networking: A Ktor WebSocket Client with an active monitoring thread for connection health.

Interception Layer: Implements NotificationListenerService.

Filtering Logic: Strictly white-listed package filtering for Telephony and SMS providers.

Event Pipeline: Converts StatusBarNotification (SBN) objects into serialized JSON structures and dispatches them via the WebSocket.

3. Detailed Technical Requirements
3.1 Connectivity & Protocol
Protocol: WebSocket (RFC 6455).

Serialization: Kotlinx.serialization (JSON).

Keep-Alive: Implement a 30-second Ping/Pong interval to prevent the local router (or M1 Router setup) from dropping the idle socket.

Reconnection: Implement an Exponential Backoff strategy (starting at 2s, capping at 60s) for the Client.

3.2 Notification Interception (Source Side)
The NotificationListenerService must override onNotificationPosted(sbn: StatusBarNotification).

SMS Filter: Intercept package com.google.android.apps.messaging or com.android.mms.

Call Filter: Intercept package com.google.android.dialer or com.android.server.telecom.

Data Extraction:

Title: Extract using Notification.EXTRA_TITLE.

Content: Extract using Notification.EXTRA_TEXT.

Priority: Map the source priority to the payload.

3.3 Notification Injection (Sink Side)
Channel Management: Create a dedicated NotificationChannel named "Mirrored Alerts" with IMPORTANCE_HIGH.

Uniqueness: Generate a consistent Notification ID by hashing the source packageName + title to prevent notification spamming while allowing updates to the same alert.

Metadata: Use setSmallIcon with a generic "Remote" icon to distinguish mirrored alerts from local ones.

3.4 Persistence & Reliability (The "Android-Proofing")
Foreground Service: Both roles must display a persistent, non-dismissible notification explaining the active bridge status.

Power Management:

Request ACTION_REQUEST_IGNORE_BATTERY_OPTIMIZATIONS.

Utilize PowerManager.WakeLock to ensure the WebSocket doesn't sleep during inactive periods.

Xiaomi Specifics: Document the need for manual "Auto-start" and "No restrictions" battery settings in HyperOS/MIUI.

4. Data Schema (JSON)
JSON
{
  "type": "NOTIFICATION_EVENT",
  "payload": {
    "id": "String (UUID/Hash)",
    "category": "SMS | CALL",
    "originDevice": "Xiaomi 11T Pro",
    "title": "String",
    "message": "String",
    "packageName": "String",
    "postedTime": Long
  }
}
5. User Interface Requirements (Jetpack Compose)
Status Dashboard: Real-time indicator of the WebSocket state (Disconnected, Connecting, Connected).

Role Switch: A prominent toggle to switch between Server and Client modes.

Configuration: * Server Mode: Display the device's Local IP.

Client Mode: Input field for the Server's IP address.

Permission Monitor: A list of required permissions (Notification Access, Battery Optimization, etc.) with their current status (Granted/Denied).

6. Security Considerations
Handshake: (Optional for Phase 1) A simple AUTH_TOKEN in the WebSocket header to ensure only your two devices can communicate.

Local-Only: The server must bind to the local network interface only.

Instructions for the AI Assistant (Codex/Cursor):
Architecture: Use a Clean Architecture approach. Separate the Domain (models), Data (Ktor/Serialization), and Presentation (Compose/ViewModel).

Threading: Use Dispatchers.IO for all networking and Dispatchers.Main for notification triggers.

Lifecycle: Ensure the WebSocket server/client is tied to the Service lifecycle, NOT the Activity lifecycle.